{
  "doc_id": "49732",
  "text": "Studies have also reported on factors which may influence outcomes of a Girdlestone procedure. For example, despite Bourne et al. [CITATION_1] reporting that patients with Gram-negative PJIs developed more postoperative wound complications, Castellanos et al. [CITATION_2] found no correlation between the type of organisms and persistence of infection, nor between limb shortening and the functional results. Of note is that patients achieved 83% satisfactory pain levels and 86% resolution of infection in this study [CITATION_3] . Kantor et al. [CITATION_4] found that adequate soft tissues with healed wounds and signs of heterotopic ossification on plain radiographs correlated well with good functional outcomes and reduced pain levels postoperatively. On the other hand, poor outcomes have been reported with elderly patients [CITATION_5] , diabetics and patients with multiple comorbidities [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Established osteoarthritis of the contralateral hip also predisposed to poor mobility and subsequent lower function after a Girdlestone procedure [CITATION_8] . Poor prognosis has also been associated with retained cement in the femoral canal as this may act as a nidus for persistent infection [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Bourne et al. [CITATION_11] also suggested a relationship between the retained cement and resultant bony sequestra and prolonged postoperative wound discharge.",
